Exploratory Data Analysis

house %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Price)) +
  geom_histogram(bins=10) +
  theme_light()

house %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Size,
             y = Price)) +
  geom_point() + 
  theme_light()

Simple Linear Regression Model

Construct a linear model:

\[ \text{Price} = m * \text{Size} + b \]

model <- lm(Price ~ Size, data = house)
model
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Price ~ Size, data = house)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)         Size  
##    -31923.7        119.8

Plot our model on top of our data:

house %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Size,
             y = Price)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_abline(slope = model$coefficients[2],
              intercept = model$coefficients[1],
              color = "red",
              size = 1) +
  theme_light()

Is this a good model?

Are the assumptions met?

  • Are the rows independent from one another?
  • Are the errors normally distributed?
plot(model)

Are our explantory variables good predictors of y?

Using the Model to Make Predictions

We can use this model to make predictions about

predict.lm(model, data.frame(Size = 2000))
##        1 
## 207644.2

Remember that you can only make predictions for values similars to whats in your dataset:

  • you shouldnt use this model to make predictions for houses much smaller than what is in our dataset (say 25 sqft) or houses much larger than what is in our dataset (say 10000 sqft)
  • if this data is collected from a particular city of neighborhood, we shouldnt use it to make predictions for other cities or neighborhoods.

Comparing Models

R-squared: the percent of variation in our response variable thats explained by our model

summary(model)$r.squared
## [1] 0.4020082
summary(model_full)$r.squared
## [1] 0.516158

AIC (Akaike Information Criterion) Lower values are better

AIC(model)
## [1] 2611.294
AIC(model_full)
## [1] 2595.901

Using the Step Function

You may be unsure which variable to leave in and which to leave out. You can feed the full model into the step function and it will decide!

Email Dataset

You can learn more about this dataset by typing ?email into the console.

Logistic Regression to Predict a Binary Variable (Spam or not spam)

winner.model <-glm(factor(spam) ~ winner,
                   data = email,
                   family = "binomial")
summary(winner.model)
